event:message
data:{"sessionId":"6a5a5bb8fe085fa6b0b185fa","messageId":"6a5a5c3e51711d12e7150828","eventIndex":370,"eventType":"statusLog","status":"processing","currentStatusLog":{"statusType":"fulfillment_completed","statusMessage":"Fulfillment completed","answer":"### Proof by contradiction\n\n1. **Assume the opposite:** suppose \\(\\sqrt{2}\\) is rational.\n\n2. Then it can be written as a fraction in lowest terms:\n   \\[\n   \\sqrt{2}=\\frac{a}{b},\n   \\]\n   where \\(a,b\\in\\mathbb Z\\), \\(b\\neq 0\\), and \\(a\\) and \\(b\\) have no common factor other than \\(1\\).\n\n3. Square both sides:\n   \\[\n   2=\\frac{a^2}{b^2}.\n   \\]\n\n4. Multiply by \\(b^2\\):\n   \\[\n   a^2=2b^2.\n   \\]\n\n5. Thus \\(a^2\\) is even. If an integer’s square is even, the integer itself must be even. Therefore, \\(a\\) is even.\n\n6. Write \\(a=2k\\) for some integer \\(k\\). Substitute this into \\(a^2=2b^2\\):\n   \\[\n   (2k)^2=2b^2.\n   \\]\n\n7. Simplifying gives:\n   \\[\n   4k^2=2b^2\n   \\quad\\Longrightarrow\\quad\n   b^2=2k^2.\n   \\]\n\n8. Therefore \\(b^2\\) is even, so \\(b\\) must also be even.\n\n9. Hence both \\(a\\) and \\(b\\) are divisible by \\(2\\). But this contradicts the assumption that \\(\\frac{a}{b}\\) was in lowest terms.\n\nTherefore, the original assumption is false, and\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\sqrt{2}\\text{ is irrational}.}\n\\]","time":"2026-07-17T16:45:57Z"}}

